, -0.027173055335879326, -0.030221739783883095, -0.031096579506993294, 0.018345125019550323, 0.0054114144295454025, -0.03870503231883049, 0.015084358863532543, 0.022202374413609505, -0.005881972145289183, 0.006819773931056261, -0.015150634571909904, 8.165378676494583e-05, -0.017165416851639748, -0.04498797282576561, -0.013056321069598198, 0.00016310045612044632, 0.027862321585416794, 0.015031338669359684, 0.027464667335152626, 0.016224302351474762, 0.011545234359800816, 0.043901052325963974, 0.025449885055422783, -0.010007637552917004, 0.0393412820994854, 0.008178426884114742, 0.008973735384643078, 0.029877105727791786, 0.016197791323065758, 0.008377254009246826, 0.016542425379157066, -0.023899033665657043, 0.030221739783883095, 0.04509401693940163, -0.018225830048322678, 0.055830687284469604, 0.026444021612405777, -0.005312000866979361, 0.017669113352894783, 0.027517689391970634, 0.0010123619576916099, 0.00747590372338891, -0.0031133031006902456, -0.02116847224533558, 0.021566126495599747, 0.014752980321645737, -0.010730043053627014, 0.006939070299267769, -0.02825997769832611, 0.026152407750487328]], "input": ["\"TOTAL SALES QUANTITY CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE\":\"Total sales quantity contribution variance = (actual sales quantity in budgeted proportions - budgeted sales quantity) * standard contribution per unit.\"", "\"SALES PERFORMANCE OF THE BUSINESS\":\"The sales performance of the business has been very good over the last year, as shown by the favourable sales quantity variance of $48,144. Overall, total revenue is 33% higher than budgeted due to an increase in the total number of valets performed. The number of mini valets increased dramatically by 99%, while full valets increased by 11%. The adverse sales mix variance of $6,554 is reflective of changes in consumer behavior due to decreased disposable incomes and longer car retention periods.\"", "\"ANALYSIS OF PRODUCTION VARIANCE AND MARKET SHARE IN STANDARD COSTING\":\"The Safe Soap Co makes environmentally-friendly soap using three basic ingredients. The standard cost of one batch of soap was $6.4. The budget for production and sales in September was 120,000 batches, but actual production and sales were 136,000 batches. The production manager made changes to improve quality and reduce material waste, including using a higher quality supplier, adjusting the product mix, and using new machinery. The sales manager reported positive customer feedback and increased orders.\"", "\"STANDARD COST OF ONE BATCH OF SOAP\":\"The standard cost of one batch of soap was $6.4, calculated as follows: Lye (0.25 kg at $10 per kg), Coconut oil (0.6 kg at $4 per kg), and Shea butter (0.5 kg at $3 per kg).\"", "\"YIELD VARIANCE FOR SEPTEMBER\":\"The yield variance for September was $9,899 favorable, calculated as follows: Total kg of materials per standard batch (0.25 + 0.6 + 0.5) = 1.35 kg. Total kg used: 181,512 should yield (181,512/1.35) 134,453.33 batches. Actual output: 136,000 batches. Surplus: 1,546.67 batches. Standard cost per batch: $6.4. Yield variance: $9,898.67 favorable.\"", "\"ACTUAL QUANTITIES OF LYE AND SHEA BUTTER USED COMPARED WITH THE STANDARD MIX\":\"The actual quantities of Lye and Shea Butter used compared with the standard mix were as follows: Lye: More than the standard mix, Shea Butter: Less than the standard mix.\"", "\"SAFE SOAP CO\":\"The Safe Soap Co makes a contribution of $3.6 on each batch of soap sold. The budgeted sales of 120,000 batches were based on achieving a market share of 10%. The actual sales of the total market in September were 1.4 million units. The market share variance for the month of September was calculated to be $14,400 adverse.\"", "\"STANDARD COSTING\":Standard costing is a cost accounting method that assigns expected costs to products and services. It involves setting standard costs for materials, labor, and overheads, and then comparing these standards to actual costs to identify variances. This method allows for variance analysis to identify differences between actual and expected costs, providing valuable insights for cost control and management.", "\"VARIANCE ANALYSIS AND IMPACT OF PRODUCTION MIX ON ORGANIC BREAD COMPANY'S COSTING\":\"The Organic Bread Company (OBC) makes a range of breads for sale direct to the public. The production process involves weighing ingredients, mixing, shaping, baking, and inspecting loaves. The standard cost card for OBC's Mixed Bloomer includes white flour, wholegrain flour, and yeast. Budgeted production was 1,000 units, but actual production was 950 units. The material mix variance for the period was calculated to be an adverse variance of $16.51.\"", "\"MATERIAL MIX VARIANCE FOR OBC\":\"Material mix variance = (Actual quantity used - Actual quantity in Standard) * Standard price\"", "\"MATERIAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS AND PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT CHALLENGES AT KAPPA CO\":\"Kappa Co produces Omega, an animal feed made by mixing and heating three ingredients: Alpha, Beta, and Gamma. The company uses a standard costing system to monitor its costs. The standard material cost for 100 kg of Omega is calculated based on the input quantities and costs of Alpha, Beta, and Gamma. The case highlights the challenges in material variance analysis and performance assessment due to factors like standard evaporation loss, varying quality and price of agricultural products, and outdated standard mix settings.\"", "\"MATERIAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Material variance analysis involves comparing the actual material costs to the standard costs to identify variances. These variances can be due to differences in material prices, usage, or mix. The analysis helps in understanding the reasons behind cost deviations and in making informed decisions to control costs.\"", "\"ALPHA\":Alpha is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients required for Omega's production. The quality and price of Alpha are variable and can change significantly from year to year. The standard cost for Alpha is $2.00 per kg.", "\"BETA\":Beta is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients required for Omega's production. The quality and price of Beta are variable and can change significantly from year to year. The standard cost for Beta is $5.00 per kg.", "\"GAMMA\":Gamma is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients essential for creating Omega. The quality and price of Gamma are variable and can change significantly from year to year. Despite these fluctuations, the standard cost for Gamma is typically $1.00 per kg.", "\"STANDARD MIX\":The \"STANDARD MIX\" refers to the predetermined proportions of Alpha, Beta, and Gamma used in the production of Omega. This mix is set by the finance department and has not been updated since the product launch five years ago."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}